story.title: Falco - Episode 1
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?

messages.text: The following is an audio call between Lynette Dixon and Cedar Creek Emergency Dispatch, placed June 18, 7:48 PM.
911, what‚Äôs your emergency?
I need to report a missing person ‚Äî my daughter.
She didn‚Äôt show up for work. Nobody knows where she is‚Äî
But we found her car.
Okay, slow down, ma‚Äôam. What‚Äôs your daughter‚Äôs name?
Elizabeth Dixon. Libby ‚Äî we call her Libby.
Okay, how old is Libby?
She‚Äôs sixteen ‚Äî sixteen years old.
And you‚Äôre her mother?
Yes ‚Äî Lynette Dixon. I think something‚Äôs happened to her‚Äî
We found her car out on Route 12.
You located her vehicle?
Yes ‚Äî the keys are still in the ignition ‚Äî her cell phone‚Äôs here‚Ä¶
She‚Äôd never leave it behind. Something must be wrong‚Äî
I need you to stay calm, ma‚Äôam.
When did you last see your daughter?
This morning, before I ran some errands ‚Äî around 10:00, maybe?
She was supposed to work at 5:00, but she didn‚Äôt show up.
Where does she work?
Scoops.
The ice cream parlor?
Yes. Her boss called when she didn‚Äôt come in for her shift‚Äî
We contacted her friends‚Äî
We went out looking for her‚Äî
And nobody‚Äôs seen her today?
No ‚Äî just me, this morning.
My oldest daughter said we have to wait 24 hours to report Libby missing‚Ä¶
But this isn‚Äôt like her ‚Äî I couldn‚Äôt wait‚Ä¶
There‚Äôs no waiting period for reports, ma‚Äôam‚Äî
You did the right thing by calling. Can you tell me what Libby looks like?
She‚Äôs about 5‚Äô5‚Äù, white, brown hair, 140 pounds.
Does she have any identifying features? A birthmark or a tattoo, maybe?
No, her father would never let her get a tattoo‚Äî
She doesn‚Äôt have any birthmarks either.
What was she wearing when you last saw her this morning?
Blue jeans, a loose blouse ‚Äî it had little pink flowers on it.
Okay. Does she have any health conditions we should be aware of?
No, she‚Äôs perfectly healthy.
Is she on any medications?
Antidepressants ‚Äî she takes antidepressants.
Has she ever been hospitalized for mental illness?
Yes, she had an episode a few months ago‚Äî
But that‚Äôs got nothing to do with this. We need to look for her ‚Äî please‚Äî
I‚Äôm gonna get a deputy out there soon, ma‚Äôam. Are you with her vehicle right now?
Yes ‚Äî we‚Äôre out on Route 12 with her car.
Who‚Äôs out there with you?
My husband, Darrence ‚Äî he‚Äôs Libby‚Äôs father.
What kind of car does Libby drive?
A Honda Civic.
Lynette‚Äôs voice pitches up an octave, as if she‚Äôs yelling over the receiver.
Darrence, what year is Libby‚Äôs car?
He says ‚Äô97 ‚Äî it‚Äôs a 1997 Honda Civic. It‚Äôs dark blue with four doors ‚Äî wait‚Äî
Her voice pitches up again.
Darrence, come over here‚Äî
Through the receiver, the operator‚Äôs voice is stern.
Ma‚Äôam, are you okay?
Lynette speaks into the phone.
She has a flat tire ‚Äî on the front driver‚Äôs side.
Okay, can you tell me your precise location so I can send the deputy to meet you?
We‚Äôre on Route 12 ‚Äî about a mile past Exit 66.
There‚Äôs an abandoned gas station across the street ‚Äî Whistle Stop ‚Äî oh my goodness!
What‚Äôs happening?
A text message just came through on Libby‚Äôs phone‚Äî
It‚Äôs from someone named ‚ÄúBronco‚Äù‚Äî
I don‚Äôt know anybody by that name‚Äî
Darrence, look at this.
Are you able to read the message, ma‚Äôam?
Yes ‚Äî my husband won‚Äôt let our daughters use a password on their phones‚Äî
He‚Äôs opening the message now ‚Äî okay, it says‚Äî
‚ÄúDid you do it?‚Äù
‚ÄúDid you do it?‚Äù
Yes ‚Äî I don‚Äôt know what it means‚Äî
There‚Äôs no message history ‚Äî they‚Äôve all been deleted‚Äî
Should we text him back?
No, don‚Äôt do anything‚Äî
Please wait by her vehicle, ma‚Äôam. I‚Äôm sending a deputy over to meet you.
Do you need me to stay on the line with you?
No ‚Äî no ‚Äî that‚Äôs okay. We‚Äôll wait for the officer.
Okay, call us back if anything changes. The deputy should be there soon.
Okay, thank you.
Investigation: Day 1
The following is a text message conversation between Special Agent Frankie Falco and Philomena Todd, Director of the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation, initiated June 20, 2:46 PM.
I‚Äôve got a missing persons case for you, Frankie. Out in Cedar Creek.
Cedar Creek ‚Äî isn‚Äôt that in the middle of nowhere?
It‚Äôs a small town, yes.
Name‚Äôs Elizabeth Dixon ‚Äî 16, missing two days.
Physical description?
I‚Äôm sending the poster.
Director Todd sends the missing persons poster to Falco.
The Sheriff‚Äôs Office can‚Äôt find a missing kid by themselves?
They think she‚Äôs a runaway‚Äî
So they phoned it in.
To be blunt, yes.
They also suspect suicide.
Does the child have a history of mental illness?
She was hospitalized for a depressive episode a few months prior‚Ä¶
But the family insists it was an isolated incident.
They‚Äôre demanding our assistance‚Äî
We have resources the sheriff doesn‚Äôt have access to.
Okay. Anything from Search & Rescue?
Libby‚Äôs vehicle was recovered on Route 12, but they didn‚Äôt find any evidence at the scene.
K9 unit?
The dogs lost Libby‚Äôs scent a few feet from her vehicle.
Theories about her disappearance?
The car had a flat tire‚Äî
The Dixons seem to think she was abducted by a passing motorist after it blew out.
But there are no suspects?
None, so the sheriff couldn‚Äôt issue an AMBER Alert‚Äî
But they entered her information in the NCIC database.
Sheriff Simmons will provide you with the case file when you arrive.
His direct line is 555-4752.
Okay, Director.
Let me warn you, the Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office is a real boys‚Äô club‚Äî
There are very few female agents on the force.
Well, mercy me, I‚Äôm just a pretty little peach.
Frankie.
I‚Äôm far too dainty for men‚Äôs police work, bless my heart.
I reckon I might break a nail.
That‚Äôs enough.
You‚Äôre an excellent agent ‚Äî that‚Äôs all that matters here.
That, and the fact that Smith and Lopez are up to their eyeballs in narcotics about now.
They get all the drug busts and I‚Äôm left looking for missing kids.
This is your assignment, Agent Falco.
I can handle it.
I know you can. Keep in mind that sheriffs are elected‚Äî
They don‚Äôt answer to Internal Affairs.
But they answer to the public.
Only during election season‚Äî
They can‚Äôt be fired or removed from office during their four-year term.
So their jobs are basically untouchable.
Yes, unless the local prosecutor files a criminal case against them for gross misconduct.
But small towns tend to protect their own.
And they won‚Äôt take kindly to our involvement in the Dixon case, will they?
Probably not, but our responsibility is to the missing child.
10-4, Director.
I‚Äôll get my stuff in order and take the sedan down to Cedar Creek at the crack of dawn.
Okay. I‚Äôll be in touch.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Sheriff Cecil Simmons of the Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office, initiated June 20, 5:13 PM.
Good evening, Sheriff Simmons. I‚Äôm Special Agent Falco with the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation.
I‚Äôll be in Cedar Creek tomorrow to assist on the Dixon case.
If you could email the case file to me, it would aid in my preparation.
There‚Äôs not much to the file. It seems likely she ran away.
I‚Äôd like to check out all of the possibilities‚Äî
I‚Äôm told the Dixons suspect an opportunistic abduction.
That‚Äôs absurd. The odds of being kidnapped by a stranger are very low.
She‚Äôs more likely to die in a plane crash.
Statistically speaking, I agree.
But I‚Äôd like to look into it, nonetheless.
What evidence leads you to think Libby ran away?
She withdrew $200 from her savings account a few days before she disappeared.
We found a fake ID in her car ‚Äî for an ‚ÄúEmily Baker,‚Äù age 21.
And her father‚Äôs a strict Southern preacher. She probably wanted some freedom.
But didn‚Äôt her vehicle have a flat tire?
So? She probably stuck her thumb out after it blew.
You think she hitch-hiked?
That, or maybe Bronco picked her up.
Bronco?
Damn it, don‚Äôt your bosses brief you prior to assignment?
Her cell phone was left in the vehicle‚Äî
Probably so we couldn‚Äôt track her whereabouts.
Her mother saw a text message from an unidentified person called ‚ÄúBronco.‚Äù
What did the text say?
‚ÄúDid you do it?‚Äù
Does that sound like a kidnapping to you?
I don‚Äôt know. This is the first I‚Äôm hearing of the Bronco text.
Did you track the number?
Of course ‚Äî straight to a prepaid phone.
A burner, the kind drug dealers use.
It‚Äôs a dead end.
But why would she leave the fake ID if she were running away?
I don‚Äôt know, maybe she forgot it.
The kid‚Äôs got issues, lady.
Are you referring to her recent hospitalization?
Yeah, she overdosed on sleeping pills back in March.
She‚Äôs a mentally unstable teen who wanted to escape an oppressive father.
Is there any evidence that her father is abusive?
Well, she showed up at the hospital with a black eye, so you tell me.
The hospital didn‚Äôt report the abuse to Children‚Äôs Services?
Libby said it was an accident.
Okay, I‚Äôd like to speak to her immediate family.
Please schedule an interview for 8:00 tomorrow morning.
I don‚Äôt work for you, Agent Falco.
I could call a press conference if you like.
Excuse me?
The town of Cedar Creek needs to know what the Sheriff‚Äôs Office is doing to protect their children.
Are you threatening me?
I‚Äôm encouraging you, Sheriff. It‚Äôs just an interview ‚Äî schedule it.
Fine.
Be here at 6:00 a.m. sharp for a briefing.
I‚Äôll bring the coffee. Also, please have a deputy track Libby‚Äôs cell phone.
It was found in her vehicle ‚Äî we have the phone in our evidence locker.
Good. I‚Äôd like to know where Libby was the morning of her disappearance.
Let‚Äôs see what her GPS tells us, okay?
I‚Äôll have Deputy Decker look into it.
Is that all, Agent?
For now, thank you.
See you at 6:00 a.m.
The following is a communication from ‚ÄúConnor Mason‚Äù to Agent Falco on the Facespace messaging app, sent June 20, 8:38 PM.
I know who you are, Agent Falco. And I know you‚Äôre on the Dixon case.
I‚Äôm warning you ‚Äî don‚Äôt get involved.
Don‚Äôt risk your pretty little head.
Stay the hell out of Cedar Creek.
Or else.
Connor Mason is offline.
